Python Syntax Basics ‚Äî Conditionals

Conditionals let your program make decisions.
They evaluate expressions and run different blocks of code depending on whether something is True or False.

Think of conditionals like the ‚Äúif this happens ‚Üí do that‚Äù logic behind every automation script.

üîπ Basic if Statement
age = 20

if age >= 18:
    print("Access granted")


If the condition is true, the code runs.
If not‚Ä¶ nothing happens.

üî∏ if/else Statement
is_member = False

if is_member:
    print("Welcome back!")
else:
    print("Please sign up!")


Use else for the fallback behavior.

üî∂ if / elif / else Chain
temperature = 85

if temperature > 90:
    print("Too hot")
elif temperature > 70:
    print("Warm")
else:
    print("Chilly")


Use elif (‚Äúelse if‚Äù) when you need multiple checks.

Only the first true condition triggers.

üö® Indentation Matters

Python doesn‚Äôt use {} or ;
Indentation defines code blocks.

Bad:

if True:
print("nope")


Good:

if True:
    print("working")


Stick to 4 spaces per indent.

üîç Comparison Operators
==   # equal
!=   # not equal
>    # greater than
<    # less than
>=   # greater or equal
<=   # less or equal


Example:

if score >= 70:
    print("Pass")

üß† Logical Operators

These combine multiple conditions:

and     # both must be true
or      # at least one must be true
not     # flips true/false


Examples:

if age > 18 and has_id:
    print("You're good")

if day == "Saturday" or day == "Sunday":
    print("Weekend vibes")

if not is_active:
    print("User inactive")

üéØ Checking Membership

Use in to check lists, strings, and sets.

allowed_roles = ["admin", "editor"]

if "admin" in allowed_roles:
    print("Access OK")

if "a" in "banana":
    print("Letter found")

üß™ Nested Conditionals

Avoid over-nesting, but sometimes you need layers:

age = 30
has_ticket = True

if age >= 18:
    if has_ticket:
        print("Enjoy the show")


Cleaner alternative using logical operators:

if age >= 18 and has_ticket:
    print("Enjoy the show")

üß© Ternary (One-Line If)

Good when you want a compact assignment:

status = "adult" if age >= 18 else "minor"


Great for quick decisions in automation scripts.

‚öôÔ∏è Real Automation Example
Auto-tag files based on size:
from pathlib import Path

file = Path("report.pdf")

if file.stat().st_size > 5_000_000:
    print("Large file, compress it")
else:
    print("Small file, upload directly")

Check API response status:
import requests

response = requests.get("https://api.example.com")

if response.status_code == 200:
    print("API working")
else:
    print("API failed")

üìù Quick Reference
if condition:
    block

if condition:
    block
else:
    block

if condition:
    block
elif condition:
    block
else:
    block

x = "OK" if condition else "Not OK"
